'''Niwa Shrine''' (にわじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Ichinomiya|Q270810|WD=Q270810|1=Ichinomiya, Aichi}}, {{ill|lt=Aichi Prefecture|Q80434|WD=Q80434|1=Aichi Prefecture}}. Its former {{ill|lt=shrine rank|Q10444029|WD=Q10444029|1=Shakaku}} was {{ill|lt=gōsha|Q134917316|WD=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}.

It is the “Niwa Shrine” of {{ill|lt=Niwa District|Q1347719|WD=Q1347719|1=Niwa District}}, {{ill|lt=Owari Province|Q514506|WD=Q514506|1=Owari Province}}, listed in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|lt=Engishiki|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}. It is said to have been the sōsha of Niwa District, and has deep ties to the {{ill|lt=Niwa clan|Q2661652|WD=Q2661652|lt=Niwa no Omi|1=Niwa clan}}.

=== Overview ===
* The founding period is unknown. One theory says it was founded in {{ill|lt=701|Q23496|WD=Q23496|1=701}} ({{ill|lt=Taihō (Japan)|Q1346269|WD=Q1346269|lt=Taihō|1=Taihō (era)}} 1). It is said to have begun when the Owari Niwa no Omi, who held influence in this area, enshrined their ancestor Kamuyaimimi-no-Mikoto.
* Its original name was Niwa Shrine. From the {{ill|lt=Kamakura period|Q236205|WD=Q236205|1=Kamakura period}} onward, it was called “Niwa Tenjin,” “Niwa Ōkami,” or “Niwa Tenjin.”
* In {{ill|lt=1537|Q6461|WD=Q6461|1=1537}} ({{ill|lt=Tenbun (era)|Q1192853|WD=Q1192853|lt=Tenbun|1=Tenbun}} 6), the shrine buildings were destroyed by war fire. They were rebuilt, but in {{ill|lt=1666|Q7585|WD=Q7585|1=1666}} ({{ill|lt=Kanbun|Q1146228|WD=Q1146228|1=Kanbun (era)}} 6) they were damaged by flood. The shrine was moved to its current site. At that time, it was rebuilt in the precincts of a {{ill|lt=Rinzai school|Q639625|WD=Q639625|1=Rinzai school}} temple (Keijizan Tōkō-ji) and renamed Myōjin-sha.
* In {{ill|lt=1870|Q7741|WD=Q7741|1=1870}} (Meiji 3), it was renamed Niwa Shrine, and in {{ill|lt=1872|Q7753|WD=Q7753|1=1872}} (Meiji 5), it became a gōsha.
* On July 28, {{ill|lt=1945|Q5240|WD=Q5240|1=1945}} (Shōwa 20), all shrine buildings were destroyed in an air raid ({{ill|lt=Ichinomiya Air Raid|Q48744775|WD=Q48744775|1=Bombing of Ichinomiya}}) during the {{ill|lt=Pacific War|Q184425|WD=Q184425|1=Pacific War}}. The current buildings were rebuilt in {{ill|lt=1948|Q5165|WD=Q5165|1=1948}} (Shōwa 23).

=== Enshrined deity ===
* {{ill|lt=Kamuyaimimi-no-Mikoto|Q11588756|WD=Q11588756|1=Kamuyaimimi}}

=== Access ===
* {{ill|lt=Meitetsu Bus|Q6810397|WD=Q6810397|1=Meitetsu Bus}}: get off at “Niwa” bus stop, 10 minutes on foot
** From {{ill|lt=Meitetsu Ichinomiya Station|Q2856589|WD=Q2856589|1=Meitetsu Ichinomiya Station}} on the {{ill|lt=Nagoya Main Line|Q1137838|WD=Q1137838|1=Meitetsu Nagoya Main Line}}/{{ill|lt=Bisai Line|Q901005|WD=Q901005|1=Meitetsu Bisai Line}} of {{ill|lt=Nagoya Railroad|Q30850|WD=Q30850|1=Meitetsu}}, or from {{ill|lt=Owari-Ichinomiya Station|Q871495|WD=Q871495|1=Owari-Ichinomiya Station}} on the {{ill|lt=Tōkaidō Main Line|Q1190152|WD=Q1190152|1=Tōkaidō Main Line}} (Meitetsu Ichinomiya Station bus terminal, platform 3), take a bus bound for “Miyata Hongō (via Niwa).”

